ovide consumers with the credible knowledge needed to make reasonable choices. He explains why these markets are characterized by the primacy of competition by qualities over competition by prices, and he identifies the conditions under which singularities are constructed or are in danger of losing their uniqueness. After demonstrating how combinations of the numerous and multiform judgment devices can be used to identify different market models, Karpik applies his analytical tools to the functioning of a large number of actual markets, including fine wines, movies, luxury goods, pop music, and legal services.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEconomicsxSociological aspects. 0aProduct differentiation. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economics / Theory.2bisacsh  aAdvertising.  aAppellation.  aBehavior.  aBulletin board system.  aBusiness consultant.  aCalculation.  aCapitalism.  aChristian Lacroix.  aClothing.  aCommoditization.  aCommodity.  aConfidence trick.  aConsideration.  aConsumer.  aCredence good.  aCriticism.  aCustomer.  aDiploma.  aDiscount store.  aDiscourse.  aDisenchantment.  aDistrust.  aEconomic efficiency.  aEconomic equilibrium.  aEconomic rent.  aEconomic sociology.  aEconomics.  aEffectiveness.  aEnron scandal.  aEntrepreneurship.  aExperience good.  aExtreme risk.  aFilmmaking.  aFlowchart.  aFordism.  aFrank Knight.  aGuideline.  aHannah Arendt.  aHarold Garfinkel.  aHigh frequency.  aIndividualism.  aIndustrial production.  aIngenuity.  aInstitution.  aInteraction.  aLaissez-faire.  aLawyer.  aLevel of analysis.  aLuxury goods.  aMainstream economics.  aMark Granovetter.  aMarket (economics).  aMarketing.  aMedia culture.  aMid-ocean ridge.  aModernity.  aMultivariate analysis.  aN. (no